content:
Thanks everyone! Appreciate everyone’s feedback. Love the community here and the fact that you all chimed in so quickly is awesome.
@Will agreed. I usually get everything setup to sound great at 0 from the start regardless, and enjoy keeping it that way for organization purposes. But the idea of not being allowed to touch them freaked me out as I’m always automating and grabbing my artist mix for blends and what not. 

@Will Melones they were going on for a bit about the fidelity side of it, talking about adjusting clip gain and adjusting volume via various plugs like @Eric Martin was saying.

@popaganda. Very much here for this #console-content. I have two approaches for console mixing:
A) Keep it on the console. Usually means keeping it on the board for a few days while people chime in with their input. Usually the band will be on board with this workflow and understand that part of the magic of this workflow is to commit to things and make decisions quickly. I was working on a console with automation, so that was useful for fine-tuning a mix by modern standards… but not impossible with static faders.
B) Have enough I/O and set each console channel as an insert in Pro Tools. This was the hybrid workflow that really worked for me. It was also the gateway to integrating outboard gear. When something needed the console treatment, I’d add the insert, get it vibing in the mix, and then once I was ready to print a pass, I’d commit all the inserts in real time. The session was getting summed in the box and everything came up perfectly for recalls. This was a great way of getting the sound and workflow but staying sane in the modern record making world.

Really helpful, thanks all @Calvin Lauber @sethearnest @Will Melones .

@willmix.studio#0 My experience with this kind of work is minimal! The thinking behind separate channels per song would be say if the drum mix wanted to be significantly different on each track, and then also just having complete freedom to go nuts on a sound without having to do everything as automation (or forget to, then wonder why the balance on track 1 is suddenly fucked).

But like you’re saying @Calvin Lauber , I think that level of detail might be impractical given the sheer amount of work to get through, and also unnecessary since as you say, it’s pretty much just one drum sound for the whole set. Maybe I could dup a channel here and there if I really wanted to go nuts on one song.

@NoahNeedleman @cian riordan @Will Melones This is awesome, thank you for your thoughts!

@NoahNeedleman Wouldn't have considered drum tuning changes. I'd be thinking about that over takes of a studio track, and flipping playlists makes it easy to check on the same section, but in this context it's the sort of thing that would've tripped me up. Like, why is the snare thwacking in song 1, but it's thwocking in song 20? Would be easy to second guies, start EQing again and ruin the rest of the show. Absolutely if you're chatting to Kaplan, it'd be great to hear - I'm sure the Discord generally would appreciate but I'd love to get his inside track, please!

@cian riordan Great shout on mindset, thank you. As @Will Melones mentioned, the energy is already great so it's not like I'm going to have to do a lot of heavy lifting. In the words of @BatMeckley (referring to the OP-1 vs Ableton), sounds like this is one to ride like a surfboard rather than drive like a bus.
